#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:5
msgid "Setting up git for NumPy development"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:7
msgid "To contribute code or documentation, you first need"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:9
msgid "git installed on your machine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:10
msgid "a GitHub account"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:11
msgid "a fork of NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:16
msgid "Install git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:18
msgid ""
"You may already have git; check by typing ``git --version``. If it's "
"installed you'll see some variation of ``git version 2.11.0``. If instead "
"you see ``command is not recognized``, ``command not found``, etc., `install "
"git <https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:24
msgid "Then set your name and email: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:26
msgid ""
"git config --global user.email you@yourdomain.example.com\n"
"git config --global user.name \"Your Name\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:33
msgid "Create a GitHub account"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:35
msgid ""
"If you don't have a GitHub account, visit https://github.com/join to create "
"one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:42
msgid "Create a NumPy fork"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:44
msgid ""
"``Forking`` has two steps -- visit GitHub to create a fork repo in your "
"account, then make a copy of it on your own machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:48
msgid "Create the fork repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:50
msgid "Log into your GitHub account."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:51
msgid "Go to the `NumPy GitHub home <https://github.com/numpy/numpy>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:52
msgid "At the upper right of the page, click ``Fork``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:56
msgid "You'll see"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:60
msgid "and then you'll be taken to the home page of your forked copy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:68
msgid "Make the local copy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:70
msgid "In the directory where you want the copy created, run ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:72
#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:172
msgid "git clone https://github.com/your-user-name/numpy.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:74
msgid "You'll see something like: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:76
msgid ""
"$ git clone https://github.com/your-user-name/numpy.git\n"
"Cloning into 'numpy'...\n"
"remote: Enumerating objects: 12, done.\n"
"remote: Counting objects: 100% (12/12), done.\n"
"remote: Compressing objects: 100% (12/12), done.\n"
"remote: Total 175837 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0), pack-reused 175825\n"
"Receiving objects: 100% (175837/175837), 78.16 MiB | 9.87 MiB/s, done.\n"
"Resolving deltas: 100% (139317/139317), done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:85
msgid ""
"A directory ``numpy`` is created on your machine. (If you already have a "
"numpy directory, GitHub will choose a different name like ``numpy-1``.) ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:89
msgid ""
"$ ls -l\n"
"total 0\n"
"drwxrwxrwx 1 bjn bjn 4096 Jun 20 07:20 numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:95
msgid "Give the name ``upstream`` to the main NumPy repo: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:97
msgid ""
"cd numpy\n"
"git remote add upstream https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:100
msgid ""
"Set up your repository so ``git pull`` pulls from ``upstream`` by default: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:103
msgid ""
"git config branch.main.remote upstream\n"
"git config branch.main.merge refs/heads/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:106
msgid "Initialize the required git submodules: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:108
msgid "git submodule update --init"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:110
msgid "Pull from upstream to get latest tag information: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:112
msgid "git pull"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:116
msgid "Look it over"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:118
msgid "The branches shown by ``git branch -a`` will include"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:120
msgid "the ``main`` branch you just cloned on your own machine"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:121
msgid ""
"the ``main`` branch from your fork on GitHub, which git named ``origin`` by "
"default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:123
msgid ""
"the ``main`` branch on the main NumPy repo, which you named ``upstream``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:128
msgid ""
"main\n"
"remotes/origin/main\n"
"remotes/upstream/main"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:132
msgid ""
"If ``upstream`` isn't there, it will be added after you access the NumPy "
"repo with a command like ``git fetch`` or ``git pull``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:136
msgid ""
"The repos shown by ``git remote -v show`` will include your fork on GitHub "
"and the main repo: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:139
msgid ""
"upstream    https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git (fetch)\n"
"upstream    https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git (push)\n"
"origin      https://github.com/your-user-name/numpy.git (fetch)\n"
"origin      https://github.com/your-user-name/numpy.git (push)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:144
msgid "``git config --list`` will include ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:146
msgid ""
"user.email=your_email@example.com\n"
"user.name=Your Name\n"
"remote.origin.url=git@github.com:your-github-id/numpy.git\n"
"remote.origin.fetch=+refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*\n"
"branch.main.remote=upstream\n"
"branch.main.merge=refs/heads/main\n"
"remote.upstream.url=https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git\n"
"remote.upstream.fetch=+refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/upstream/*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:160
msgid "Optional: set up SSH keys to avoid passwords"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:162
msgid ""
"Cloning your NumPy fork repo required no password, because it read the "
"remote repo without changing it. Later, though, submitting your pull "
"requests will write to it, and GitHub will ask for your username and "
"password -- even though it's your own repo. You can eliminate this "
"authentication without compromising security by `setting up SSH keys \\ "
"<https://help.github.com/en/github/authenticating-to-github/connecting-to-"
"github-with-ssh>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:169
msgid ""
"**If you set up the keys before cloning**, the instructions above change "
"slightly. Instead of ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:174
msgid "run ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:176
msgid "git clone git@github.com:your-user-name/numpy.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:178
msgid ""
"and instead of showing an ``https`` URL,  ``git remote -v`` will show ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:180
msgid ""
"origin  git@github.com:your-user-name/numpy.git (fetch)\n"
"origin  git@github.com:your-user-name/numpy.git (push)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/gitwash/development_setup.rst:184
msgid ""
"**If you have cloned already** and want to start using SSH, see `Switching "
"remote URLs from HTTPS to SSH \\ <https://help.github.com/en/github/using-"
"git/changing-a-remotes-url#switching-remote-urls-from-https-to-ssh>`_."
msgstr ""
